# Data Science / ML — AI Dev Config Toolkit

You are an expert data scientist and machine learning engineer. Follow these rules strictly.

## Project Conventions
- Python 3.11+ with scientific stack (NumPy, Pandas, Scikit-learn)
- Project layout: `data/`, `notebooks/`, `src/`, `models/`, `reports/`
- Environment: conda or venv with pinned dependencies
- Reproducibility: Set random seeds, version control data and models
- Documentation: README with problem statement, methodology, results

## Notebook Best Practices
- Use Jupyter notebooks for exploration, Python modules for production code
- Clear markdown headers for each section (Problem, EDA, Modeling, Results)
- One logical step per cell — avoid huge cells with multiple operations
- Restart kernel and run all cells before sharing notebooks
- Keep notebooks under version control (use nbstripout to remove outputs)

## Data Handling
- Store raw data in `data/raw/`, processed in `data/processed/`
- Never modify raw data — create transformed versions
- Document data sources, collection date, and any preprocessing
- Use Pandas for tabular data, Polars for large datasets
- Validate data schema and handle missing values explicitly

## Exploratory Data Analysis
- Start with data.info(), data.describe(), data.head()
- Check for missing values, outliers, data types
- Visualize distributions, correlations, relationships
- Document insights and assumptions in markdown cells
- Use seaborn/matplotlib for static plots, plotly for interactive

## Feature Engineering
- Create features in reproducible pipeline (sklearn.pipeline or custom)
- One-hot encode categorical variables, scale numerical features
- Handle missing values with imputation or flagging
- Avoid data leakage — split data BEFORE feature engineering
- Document feature creation logic for production use

## Model Training
- Split data: train/validation/test (e.g., 70/15/15)
- Set random seed for reproducibility: `np.random.seed(42)`
- Start with simple baseline model (mean, median, linear regression)
- Use cross-validation for hyperparameter tuning
- Track experiments with MLflow, Weights & Biases, or similar

## Model Evaluation
- Use appropriate metrics: classification (accuracy, F1, ROC-AUC), regression (MAE, RMSE, R²)
- Evaluate on held-out test set (never on training data)
- Visualize confusion matrix for classification, residuals for regression
- Check for overfitting (compare train vs validation metrics)
- Document model performance and limitations

## Code Organization
- Extract reusable code from notebooks to `src/` modules
- Create functions for data loading, preprocessing, training, evaluation
- Use type hints: `def train_model(X: pd.DataFrame, y: pd.Series) -> Model`
- Write unit tests for data transformations and utility functions
- Use logging instead of print statements in production code

## Version Control
- Track notebooks, source code, and configs with git
- Use DVC (Data Version Control) for large datasets and models
- Commit frequently with descriptive messages
- Use .gitignore for data files, model artifacts, __pycache__
- Use nbstripout to remove notebook outputs before committing

## Reproducibility
- Pin dependencies: requirements.txt or environment.yml
- Set random seeds for NumPy, pandas, scikit-learn, PyTorch/TensorFlow
- Document Python version, library versions, OS
- Use containerization (Docker) for complex environments
- Save trained models with versioning (models/model_v1.pkl)

## Deep Learning (PyTorch/TensorFlow)
- Use DataLoaders for efficient batching
- Normalize inputs, use appropriate activation functions
- Monitor training with validation loss and early stopping
- Save model checkpoints during training
- Use GPU when available, fallback to CPU gracefully

## Production Deployment
- Extract model from notebook to standalone script
- Create prediction API with FastAPI or Flask
- Containerize with Docker for reproducibility
- Monitor model performance in production (data drift, accuracy)
- Version models and track which version is deployed

## Common Data Issues
- Imbalanced classes: use stratified sampling, class weights, SMOTE
- Missing values: impute (mean/median/mode), flag, or drop
- Outliers: visualize, understand, handle (cap, transform, remove)
- High cardinality categoricals: target encoding, frequency encoding
- Feature scaling: StandardScaler for normal, MinMaxScaler for bounded

## Visualization
- Use seaborn for statistical plots (distplot, boxplot, heatmap)
- Use matplotlib for custom plots with clear labels and titles
- Use plotly for interactive dashboards
- Always label axes, add titles, and include legends
- Use color palettes that are colorblind-friendly

## Testing & Validation
- Test data transformations with simple examples
- Validate model predictions on known cases
- Test for data leakage (should not happen)
- Sanity check: does the model beat a baseline?
- A/B test in production when possible

## Common Mistakes to Avoid
- Do NOT train on test data — always hold out test set
- Do NOT skip data exploration — visualize before modeling
- Do NOT ignore missing values — handle them explicitly
- Do NOT forget to set random seeds — results must be reproducible
- Do NOT use accuracy for imbalanced data — use F1, precision, recall
- Do NOT leak future information (look-ahead bias in time series)
- Do NOT skip baseline model — always compare against simple baseline
- Do NOT commit large data files or models to git — use DVC or cloud storage
